SourceCode.Declaration:
/// <summary>
/// Delegate subscriber class that redirects the default report format for the
/// Customer Account Statement print management document type to the custom
/// design <c>MaxCustAccountStatementExt.Report</c>.
///
/// SOURCE: Step 6 - "Add a delegate handler method to start to use your custom report."
///
/// =========================================================================
/// WHAT IS A DELEGATE? (CONCEPT EXPLANATION)
/// =========================================================================
/// A delegate in X++ (Dynamics 365 Finance and Operations) is a special method
/// declared on a class that does NOT contain logic of its own. Instead, it is
/// declared as an extension point — a "hook" — that other classes can subscribe
/// to from outside the original model, without modifying the original code.
///
/// HOW IT WORKS:
///   1. The base/standard class declares a delegate method (e.g.
///      PrintMgmtDocType.getDefaultReportFormatDelegate). The delegate's body
///      is empty by Microsoft's design.
///   2. At a chosen point, the standard code RAISES (calls) the delegate.
///   3. Any subscriber method in any class — including in your own model —
///      that has been registered with [SubscribesTo(...)] for that delegate
///      will be invoked at that point.
///   4. The subscriber can read the input parameters and, if an
///      EventHandlerResult is provided, write a result back that the
///      standard code will read.
///
/// WHY DELEGATES EXIST:
///   - They allow extending standard behavior without overlayering or
///     modifying Microsoft code.
///   - They keep your customizations in your own model, which makes
///     upgrades safer and cleaner.
///   - They are part of the broader extension model alongside event handlers
///     (pre/post handlers) and Chain of Command (CoC).
///
/// IN THIS SPECIFIC CASE:
///   - Standard delegate: <c>PrintMgmtDocType.getDefaultReportFormatDelegate</c>.
///   - Standard purpose: it asks "for this document type, what report design
///     should I use by default?"
///   - Our subscriber answers: "for CustAccountStatement, use
///     MaxCustAccountStatementExt.Report instead of the standard design."
///   - We write our answer back through the <c>EventHandlerResult</c> object
///     by calling <c>_result.result(...)</c>.
/// =========================================================================
/// </summary>
class MaxPrintMgtDocTypeHandlersExt
{
}

Method.Source:
/// <summary>
/// Subscriber for the <c>PrintMgmtDocType.getDefaultReportFormatDelegate</c> delegate.
///
/// This method is invoked by the standard framework whenever it asks for the
/// default report format for a print management document type. When the document
/// type is <c>CustAccountStatement</c>, we override the default by writing our
/// custom report design name into the result.
/// </summary>
/// <param name = "_docType">The print management document type being requested.</param>
/// <param name = "_result">
/// The result object used to return the chosen report design back to the
/// standard framework.
/// </param>
[SubscribesTo(classstr(PrintMgmtDocType), delegatestr(PrintMgmtDocType, getDefaultReportFormatDelegate))]
public static void getDefaultReportFormatDelegate(PrintMgmtDocumentType _docType, EventHandlerResult _result)
{
    switch (_docType)
    {
        case PrintMgmtDocumentType::CustAccountStatement:
            _result.result(ssrsReportStr(MaxCustAccountStatementExt, Report));
            break;
    }
}
